    article_date=2024-03-16+T00:00:00Z
>

  <section class="post-body">


    <aside class="post-index">
      <a class="anchor-link" href="#Installation"><h2>Installation</h2></a>
      <a class="anchor-link" href="#Use"><h2>Use</h2></a>
    </aside>


    <div class="post-body-content">
      
      <section class="section-block-markdown-cell">
      <h1 id="Git-sim">Git-sim<a class="anchor-link" href="#Git-sim"><img decoding="async" class="link-img" width="24px" height="24px" alt="link image 3" src={svg_paths.link_svg_path}/></a></h1>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section-block-markdown-cell">
      <p>Are you afraid to do a <code>git rebase</code>? Or a <code>git reset</code>? Or any other git command? Don't worry, because with <code>git-sim</code> you'll be able to see before you do it what's going to happen so you can make the right decision.</p>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section-block-markdown-cell">
      <p>This notebook has been automatically translated to make it accessible to more people, please let me know if you see any typos.</p>
      <h2 id="Installation">Installation<a class="anchor-link" href="#Installation"><img decoding="async" class="link-img" width="24px" height="24px" alt="link image 4" src={svg_paths.link_svg_path}/></a></h2><p>To install <code>git-sim</code> we first need to install <code>manim</code>, which is a python library for making animations. For this we can install it with pip:</p>
      <div class="highlight"><pre><span></span>pip<span class="w"> </span>install<span class="w"> </span>manim
      <span class="sb">```</span>
      
      or<span class="w"> </span>with<span class="w"> </span>conda
      
      <span class="sb">````</span>bash
      conda<span class="w"> </span>install<span class="w"> </span>-c<span class="w"> </span>conda-forge<span class="w"> </span>manim
      <span class="sb">```</span>
      </pre></div>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section-block-markdown-cell">
      <p>Once <code>manim</code> is installed we can install <code>git-sim</code> with pip:</p>
      <div class="highlight"><pre><span></span>pip<span class="w"> </span>install<span class="w"> </span>git-sim
      <span class="sb">```</span>
      </pre></div>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section-block-markdown-cell">
      <h2 id="Use">Use<a class="anchor-link" href="#Use"><img decoding="async" class="link-img" width="24px" height="24px" alt="link image 5" src={svg_paths.link_svg_path}/></a></h2>
      </section>
      
      <section class="section-block-markdown-cell">
      <p>Now that we have it installed we go to a repository and test any git command changing <code>git</code> for <code>git-sim</code>. For example, if in a repository of mine I do a <code>git-sim reset --hard HEAD~1</code> it will show me an animation of how the rebase would look like before doing it.</p>
      <p><img decoding="async" onerror="this.parentNode.removeChild(this)" alt="git-sim" src="http://maximofn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/git-sim-scaled.webp" width="1200" height="675"/></p>
      <p>As we can see it is showing me that if I do <code>git reset --hard HEAD~1</code> it would go from commit <code>ae757a8</code> to commit <code>3754c64</code> and that it would also remove the changes in the files indicated in <code>Changes deleted from</code>.</p>
      </section>
      






    </div>

  </section>

